The Nigerian Army School of Infantry yesterday graduated 1,106 Starter Point Integrated Services (SPIS) Special Forces students at Camp Seleya in Jaji Military Cantonment, Kaduna State. The acting director, Army Public Relations, Col. Sagir Musa, said that the graduands are officers and soldiers of 81 Battalion, 198 and 199 Special Forces’ Battalions. The chief of policy and plans (CPP), Lt-Gen. Lamidi Adeosun, who represented the chief of army staff (COAS),  Lt-Gen. Tukur Buratai, commended the graduands for their hard work, discipline and for putting in their best during the course. He also commended the tactical simulation conducted as part of the high points of the ceremony by the Special Forces. The COAS urged them to put their newly-acquired special skills to use in meeting the operational objectives of the Nigerian Army and the country at large. He stated that Nigerians are appreciative of the troops’ sacrifices and urged them to be prepared to give their best all the time. In his welcome address, the commandant of NASI, Maj-Gen Kevin  Aligbe, stated that the 12-week special training covered subjects like close contact combat, skills at arms, unexpected incident operations and first aid among others.